In <1993Mar18.144852.2598@vixvax.mgi.com> cepek@vixvax.mgi.com writes:
>In article <19930317.104632.975@almaden.ibm.com>,
>tarnold@vnet.IBM.COM (Todd W. Arnold) writes:
>> With any biometric system, you have to "enroll" before you can start to use
>> it.  Enrollment collects sample data, which will later be compared with the
>> data you present when you try to verify.  The reference data may be stored in
>> a central database, but it's usually more effective if you can make it
>> portable, so it goes everywhere the individual goes.  In our case, we put
>> the signature reference data on a smart card.
>
>Doesn't this leave the smart card itself as a vulnerable item?  For
>example, if I create a smart card for myself by duplicating your card's
>data but substitute my signature metrics instead, can't I masquerade as
>you?  In a central database, at least you have physical security over
>the authorizing data.  [Perhaps I've been watching too many War_Games/
>Sneakers/etc. movies :-]
>_______________________________________________________________________

The signature data on the smart card itself are encrypted.  You need
the right key to manipulate them.

